# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: resize-observer
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] In computer programming, a **callback** is a programming pattern in which a function reference is passed from one context (consumer) to another (provider) such that the provider can call the function.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] If the function accesses state or functionality of the consumer, then the call is *back* to the consumer – backwards compared to the normal flow of control in which a consumer calls a provider.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] A function that accepts a callback parameter may be designed to call back before returning to its caller.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] But, more typically, a callback reference is stored by the provider so that it can call the function later (as *deferred*).
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] If the provider invokes the callback on the same thread as the consumer, then the call is *blocking*, a.k.a.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] If instead, the provider invokes the callback on a different thread, then the call is *non-blocking*, a.k.a.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] A callback can be likened to leaving instructions with a tailor for what to do when a suit is ready, such as calling a specific phone number or delivering it to a given address.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] These instructions represent a callback: a function provided in advance to be executed later, often by a different part of the system and not necessarily by the one that received it.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] The difference between a general function reference and a callback can be subtle, and some use the terms interchangeably but distinction generally depends on programming intent.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] If the intent is like the telephone callback – that the original called party communicates back to the original caller – then it's a callback.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] A blocking callback runs in the execution context of the function that passes the callback.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] A deferred callback can run in a different context such as during interrupt or from a thread.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] As such, a deferred callback can be used for synchronization and delegating work to another thread.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] A callback can be used for event handling.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] Often, consuming code registers a callback for a particular type of event.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] When that event occurs, the callback is called.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] Callbacks are often used to program the graphical user interface (GUI) of a program that runs in a windowing system.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] The application supplies a reference to a custom callback function for the windowing system to call.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] The windowing system calls this function to notify the application of events like mouse clicks and key presses.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] A callback can be used to implement asynchronous processing.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] A caller requests an action and provides a callback to be called when the action completes which might be long after the request is made.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] A callback can be used to implement polymorphism.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] In the following pseudocode, `say_hi` can take either `write_status` or `write_error`.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] The callback technology is implemented differently by programming language.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] In assembly, C, C++, Pascal, Modula-2 and other languages, a callback function is stored internally as a function pointer.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] Using the same storage allows different languages to directly share callbacks without a design-time or runtime interoperability layer.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] For example, the Windows API is accessible via multiple languages, compilers and assemblers.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] C++ also allows objects to provide an implementation of the function call operation.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] The Standard Template Library accepts these objects (called *functors*) as parameters.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] Many dynamic languages, such as JavaScript, Lua, Python, Perl and PHP, allow a function object to be passed.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] CLI languages such as C# and Visual Basic (.NET) (VB.NET) provide a type-safe encapsulating function reference known as delegate.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] Events and event handlers, as used in .NET languages, provide for callbacks.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] Functional programming languages generally support first-class functions, which can be passed as callbacks to other functions, stored as data or returned from functions.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] Many languages, including Perl, Python, Ruby, Smalltalk, C++ (11+), C# and VB.NET (new versions) and most functional languages, support lambda expressions, unnamed functions with inline syntax, that generally act as callbacks.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] In some languages, including Scheme, ML, JavaScript, Perl, Python, Smalltalk, PHP (since 5.3.0), C++ (11+), Java (since 8), and many others, a lambda can be a closure, i.e., can access variables locally defined in the context in which the lambda is defined.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] In an object-oriented programming language such as Java versions before function-valued arguments, the behavior of a callback can be achieved by passing an object that implements an interface.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] The methods of this object are callbacks.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] In PL/I and ALGOL 60, a callback procedure may need to be able to access local variables in containing blocks, so it is called through an *entry variable* containing both the entry point and context information.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] Callbacks have a wide variety of uses, for example in error signaling: a Unix program might not want to terminate immediately when it receives SIGTERM, so to make sure that its termination is handled properly, it would register the cleanup function as a callback.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] Another common use for callbacks in C is with C standard library functions used for sorting (`qsort()`) and searching (`lsearch()`, `bsearch()`) where a comparator function is passed as an argument to the routine to determine the collation order.
[src:resize-observer/callback-computer-programming] Callbacks may also be used to control whether a function acts or not: Xlib allows custom predicates to be specified to determine whether a program wishes to handle an event.
