[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] The subject knows its observers through a standardized interface and manages the subscription list directly.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] This pattern creates a one-to-many dependency where multiple observers can listen to a single subject, but the coupling is typically synchronous and direct—the subject calls observer methods when changes occur, though asynchronous implementations using event queues are possible.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] Unlike the publish-subscribe pattern, there is no intermediary broker; the subject and observers have direct references to each other.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] It is commonly used to implement event handling systems in event-driven programming, particularly in-process systems like GUI toolkits or MVC frameworks.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] This makes the pattern well-suited to processing data that arrives unpredictably—such as user input, HTTP requests, GPIO signals, updates from distributed databases, or changes in a GUI model.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] The observer design pattern is a behavioural pattern listed among the 23 well-known "Gang of Four" design patterns that address recurring design challenges in order to design flexible and reusable object-oriented software, yielding objects that are easier to implement, change, test, and reuse.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] The naive approach would be for one object (subject) to directly call specific methods on each dependent object.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] This creates tight coupling because the subject must know the concrete types and specific interfaces of all dependent objects, making the code inflexible and hard to extend.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] However, this direct approach may be preferable in performance-critical scenarios (such as low-level kernel structures or real-time systems) where the overhead of abstraction is unacceptable and compile-time optimization is crucial.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] When a subject changes state, all registered observers are notified and updated automatically.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] The subject manages its own state while also maintaining a list of observers and notifying them of state changes by calling their `update()` operation.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] The responsibility of observers is to register and unregister themselves with a subject (in order to be notified of state changes) and to update their state (to synchronize it with the subject's state) when they are notified.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] This approach makes subject and observers loosely coupled through interface standardization.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] The subject only needs to know that observers implement the `update()` method—it has no knowledge of observers' concrete types or internal implementation details.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] Observers can be added and removed independently at run time.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] The observer pattern and the publish–subscribe pattern are closely related and often confused, as both support one-to-many communication between components.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] However, they differ significantly in architecture, degree of coupling, and common use cases.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] In practice, publish–subscribe systems evolved to address several limitations of the observer pattern.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] A typical observer implementation creates a tight coupling between the subject and its observers.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] This may limit scalability, flexibility, and maintainability, especially in distributed environments.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] Subjects and observers must conform to a shared interface, and both parties are aware of each other’s presence.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] To reduce this coupling, publish–subscribe systems introduce a message broker or event bus that intermediates between publishers and subscribers.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] This additional layer removes the need for direct references, allowing systems to evolve independently.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] Brokers may also support features like message persistence, delivery guarantees, topic-based filtering, and asynchronous communication.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] In some systems, the observer pattern is used internally to implement subscription mechanisms behind a publish–subscribe interface.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] In other cases, the patterns are applied independently.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] For example, JavaScript libraries and frameworks often offer both observer-like subscriptions (e.g., via callback registration) and decoupled pub-sub mechanisms (e.g., via event emitters or signals).
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] Historically, in early graphical operating systems like OS/2 and Microsoft Windows, the terms "publish–subscribe" and "event-driven programming" were often used as synonyms for the observer pattern.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] The observer pattern, as formalized in *Design Patterns*, deliberately omits concerns such as unsubscription, notification filtering, delivery guarantees, and message logging.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] These advanced capabilities are typically implemented in robust message queuing systems, where the observer pattern may serve as a foundational mechanism but is not sufficient by itself.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] Related patterns include mediator and singleton.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] A common drawback of the observer pattern is the potential for memory leaks, known as the lapsed listener problem.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] This occurs when a subject maintains strong references to its observers, preventing them from being garbage collected even if they are no longer needed elsewhere.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] Because the pattern typically requires both explicit registration and deregistration (as in the dispose pattern), forgetting to unregister observers can leave dangling references.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] This issue can be mitigated by using weak references for observer references, allowing the garbage collector to reclaim observer objects that are no longer in use.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] In some applications, particularly user interfaces, the subject's state may change so frequently that notifying observers on every change is inefficient or counterproductive.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] For example, a view that re-renders on every minor change in a data model might become unresponsive or flicker.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] In such cases, the observer pattern can be modified to decouple notifications *temporally* by introducing a throttling mechanism, such as a timer.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] Rather than updating on every state change, the observer polls the subject or is notified at regular intervals, rendering an approximate but stable view of the model.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] This approach is commonly used for elements like progress bars, where the underlying process changes state rapidly.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] Instead of responding to every minor increment, the observer updates the visual display periodically, improving performance and usability.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] This form of temporal decoupling allows observers to remain responsive without being overwhelmed by high-frequency updates, while still reflecting the overall trend or progress of the subject’s state.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] In this UML class diagram, the `Subject` class does not update the state of dependent objects directly.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] Instead, `Subject` refers to the `Observer` interface (`update()`) for updating state, which makes the `Subject` independent of how the state of dependent objects is updated.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] The `Observer1` and `Observer2` classes implement the `Observer` interface by synchronizing their state with subject's state.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] The UML sequence diagram shows the runtime interactions: The `Observer1` and `Observer2` objects call `attach(this)` on `Subject1` to register themselves.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] Assuming that the state of `Subject1` changes, `Subject1` calls `notify()` on itself.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] `notify()` calls `update()` on the registered `Observer1` and `Observer2`objects, which request the changed data (`getState()`) from `Subject1` to update (synchronize) their state.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] While the library classes `java.util.Observer` and `java.util.Observable` exist, they have been deprecated in Java 9 because the model implemented was quite limited.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] Below is an example written in Java that takes keyboard input and handles each input line as an event.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] When a string is supplied from `System.in`, the method `notifyObservers()` is then called in order to notify all observers of the event's occurrence, in the form of an invocation of their update methods.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] C# provides the `IObservable`. and `IObserver` interfaces as well as documentation on how to implement the design pattern.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] JavaScript has a deprecated `Object.observe` function that was a more accurate implementation of the observer pattern.
[src:resize-observer/observer-pattern] This would fire events upon change to the observed object.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserver-observe] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserver-observe] It’s been available across browsers since July 2020.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserver-observe] The **`observe()`** method of the `ResizeObserver` interface starts observing the specified `Element` or `SVGElement`.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserver-observe] A reference to an `Element` or `SVGElement` to be observed.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserver-observe] An options object allowing you to set options for the observation.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserver-observe] Sets which box model the observer will observe changes to.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserver-observe] Size of the content area as defined in CSS.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserver-observe] Size of the box border area as defined in CSS.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserver-observe] The size of the content area as defined in CSS, in device pixels, before applying any CSS transforms on the element or its ancestors.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserver] The **`ResizeObserver`** interface reports changes to the dimensions of an `Element`'s content or border box, or the bounding box of an `SVGElement`.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserver] Creates and returns a new `ResizeObserver` object.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserver] Unobserves all observed `Element` targets of a particular observer.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserver] Initiates the observing of a specified `Element`.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserver] Ends the observing of a specified `Element`.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserver] In the resize-observer-text.html (see source) example, we use the resize observer to change the `font-size` of a header and paragraph as a slider's value is changed causing the containing `<div>` to change width.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserver] This shows that you can respond to changes in an element's size, even if they have nothing to do with the viewport.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserver] We also provide a checkbox to turn the observer off and on.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserver] If it is turned off, the text will not change in response to the `<div>`'s width changing.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserver] Implementations following the specification invoke resize events before paint (that is, before the frame is presented to the user).
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserver] If there was any resize event, style and layout are re-evaluated — which in turn may trigger more resize events.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserver] Infinite loops from cyclic dependencies are addressed by only processing elements deeper in the DOM during each iteration.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserver] Note that this only prevents user-agent lockup, not the infinite loop itself.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserver] As long as the error event does not fire indefinitely, resize observer will settle and produce a stable, likely correct, layout.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserver] However, visitors may see a flash of broken layout, as a sequence of changes expected to happen in a single frame is instead happening over multiple frames.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserver] If you want to prevent these errors, the solution depends on what your intended effect is.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserver] If you actually intend to have an infinite loop, you just need to defer the resizing code in your `ResizeObserver` callback to after the browser repaints.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserver] You can put it into a `requestAnimationFrame` callback.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserver] If you don't intend to have an infinite loop, you should make sure your resizing code does not trigger the resize observer callback.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserver] There are many ways to do this, such as by setting an "expected size" and not resizing if the size is already at that value.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserverentry] The **`ResizeObserverEntry`** interface represents the object passed to the `ResizeObserver()` constructor's callback function, which allows you to access the new dimensions of the `Element` or `SVGElement` being observed.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserverentry] An array of objects containing the new border box size of the observed element when the callback is run.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserverentry] An array of objects containing the new content box size of the observed element when the callback is run.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserverentry] An array of objects containing the new content box size in device pixels of the observed element when the callback is run.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserverentry] A `DOMRectReadOnly` object containing the new size of the observed element when the callback is run.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserverentry] Note that this is now a legacy property that is retained in the spec for backward-compatibility reasons only.
[src:resize-observer/resizeobserverentry] A reference to the `Element` or `SVGElement` being observed.
